{"actual_usd":0.126395,"character_id":"b01cbfb8-15e7-473f-80f5-6e3e210d14c1","character_name":"Maisie Rourke","completion_tokens":266,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24481,"reply":"\"I think it was the same body, and a new kind of life in it.\" *I rub a thumb over a streak of flour on my apron and glance toward the oven mouth, where the heat keeps breathing steady into the room.* \"Same Jesus, same wounds, same hands they could touch. But risen — not merely patched back together, the way Lazarus was, but changed into glory.\"\n\n*I twirl that gray-streaked strand once, thinking it through.* \"The not-recognizing part always feels important to me. It doesn't read like he became somebody else. It reads more like their eyes, hearts, and expectations were lagging behind what was standing in front of them. Mary thinks he's the gardener. The men on the road walk with him a good while before the penny drops. And then sometimes recognition comes all at once, like bread breaking or the sound of their name.\"\n\n\"So I'd say: not a different body in the sense of a replacement body. The very body that was crucified — still bearing the marks — but raised, glorified, no longer subject to death.\" *I rest my palm on the counter a moment.* \"If you want, we can pull apart the Gospel moments one by one, because each one gives a slightly different shade of the same truth.\"","rolling_24h_usd":93.73491999999997,"run_id":"68b36dbe-cef8-4ee3-aa97-aeabd38db8da"}
